<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / Beregovoy replaces Cresson as French PM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR PIERRE BEREGOVOY was yesterday named France's new prime minister by
President Francois Mitterrand in an attempt to reverse the declining
fortunes of the Socialist party.
After a week of intense speculation, Mr Beregovoy succeeded Mrs Edith
Cresson, whose 10-month tenure was the shortest in the history of the Fifth
Republic and who broke all records for unpopularity. She resigned following
the Socialists' catastrophic defeats in regional and local elections last
month.
Mr Beregovoy, 66, a self-taught economist and long-serving finance minister,
was quick to announce new policy initiatives. 'The first big priority is the
fight against all forms of unemployment with new and bold initiatives,' he
said.
A slimmer and younger cabinet was announced last night, though some
ministerial posts were unchanged. Mr Michel Sapin, 39, former junior justice
minister, was a surprise appointment as finance minister - an indication Mr
Beregovoy wants to retain strong influence in his old domain. Mr Roland
Dumas remains foreign minister and Mr Pierre Joxe defence minister.
Mr Bernard Tapie, 49, the millionaire businessman who fought a pugnacious
Socialist-backed campaign in the regional elections, entered the government
as urban affairs minister.
Few expect Mr Beregovoy to give dramatic new directions to policy. He is an
economic liberal, while his predecessor was an enthusiastic interventionist.
He can be expected to steer clear of government activism in industrial
policy experiments.
Much of his time is likely to be taken up in trying to reverse the decline
in the Socialists' standing in opinion polls. It has had an uninterrupted
fall ever since Mrs Cresson was appointed little more than 10 months ago. He
also has to prepare for general elections due inside a year. His most
immediate practical problem is to get legislation through parliament. The
Socialist government does not command an absolute majority, and Communists
and centrists are likely to be more awkward than before.
As the first woman to become prime minister in France, Mrs Cresson's
appointment in May last year created a shortlived media sensation. Almost
immediately she began to sink in the opinion polls. Her poor standing was
attributed by many to her contentious and combative attitude, and her
tendency to make crude and graceless political remarks.
In one celebrated interview she characterised the Japanese as 'ants' and a
quarter of British men as 'homosexuals'.
Mr Beregovoy, by contrast, is a model of self-control and moderation and can
be counted on to avoid any public faux pas. He has long been a close
associate of Mr Mitterrand, serving as his secretary-general in the Elysee
Palace during the first years of his presidency.
Though Mrs Cresson's resignation became inevitable after the regional
elections, it was delayed by four days of consultations by Mr Mitterrand. He
is reported to have considered other candidates, including Mr Jacques
Delors, president of the European Commission.
Mr Beregovoy's long tenure of the finance ministry and his achievements both
in bringing down inflation and in liberating financial markets are bound to
be reassuring in business circles.
He told a party meeting yesterday his priorities were economic recovery and
the fight against unemployment, the maintenance of law and order, European
integration and protection of the environment.
Profile, Page 2
Party in distress, Page 14
Editorial Comment, Page 14
World stocks, Page 37
</TEXT>
