<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / Labour hints at deal on PR
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday signalled a willingness to strike a deal with other parties
on electoral reform as Mr John Major closed off the option of an accord with
the Liberal Democrats to save his prime ministership.
With the looming prospect of a hung parliament next Thursday's general
election, Mr Major said the Liberal Democrats' calls for electoral reform
would lead to damaging uncertainty and indecision.
'There are no circumstances in which I would introduce proportional
representation,' he pledged.
However, Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, shifted in the opposite
direction, with a pledge - if elected - to open membership of the party's
inquiry on electoral reform, the 'Plant committee', to other political
parties.
Senior Labour officials denied it was a deliberate response to the Liberal
Democrats' surge in opinion polls, describing the move as part of a
pre-agreed strategy to broaden the appeal of Labour policies. The move was
swiftly derided by the Liberal Democrats.
However, senior colleagues of Mr Kinnock indicated that the stance Labour
was formulating on constitutional reform - including its pledge to Scottish
devolution - might be enough to split off some Liberal Democrat MPs in the
event of a hung parliament.
To the annoyance of Liberal Democrats, Mr Kinnock again refused to make
public his own views on proportional representation. Liberal Democrat
strategists, however, are delighted to have set constitutional reform on the
election agenda.
During a tour of the west country, Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat
leader, said Mr Kinnock was 'wobbling on the fence'. His principal term for
working with another party in government is a commitment to legislation on
proportional representation in the first Queen's speech.
Mr Ashdown believes the system of proportional representation could then be
decided in time for legislation to be passed within a year, followed by a
referendum prior to enactment.
However, Mr Major said yesterday that proportional representation was being
rejected by political leaders in other countries.
'Some countries would like to get rid of it. . . They cannot get
governments, with clear majorities, to take difficult decisions', he said.
'You are in a perpetual state of campaigning, backstairs deals and trying to
cobble together deals for individual policies. That is no way to run this
country at all.'
Meanwhile, Mr Kinnock told journalists that he wanted a broad consensus for
Labour's programme. In government, he would extend membership of the Plant
committee, chaired by Professor Raymond Plant, to other political parties
and representatives of churches, trade unions and business.
'It would be extremely dog-in-the-manger if parties like the Conservatives
and the Liberal (Democrats) were not to take full advantage of the
invitation,' Mr Kinnock said.
Labour remains publicly confident of winning an overall majority and
dismissed the suggestion that it might enter a coalition. It will today
publish a 'Queen's speech' outlining its legislative programme for a first
parliamentary session, including measures on training and on a Scottish
parliament .
With the Tories confident that economic competence remains one of their
strongest cards, Mr Major warned that Labour would prevent the recovery that
he insisted had begun.
Speaking in south London, Mr Major used the example of Tuesday's Pounds
1.3bn fall in share prices after polls showed a clear Labour lead, to warn
of the disastrous economic consequences of a Labour administration. 'One
rogue poll, a glimmer of thought that there might be a Labour government,'
and Pounds 1.3bn was wiped off share prices, he said.
Mr Kinnock last night admitted to making errors of judgment in supporting
unilateral nuclear disarmament and in failing to campaign to change Labour's
policy on the European Community after the 1975 referendum.
