<DOCNO>FT922-14981</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDCA8ADFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920403
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Hudson modernisation will boost
output
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUDSON BAY, whose Flin Flon metallurgical operations in Manitoba were
threatened with closure because they could not meet new environmental
regulations, is on course for a substantial expansion and cut in production
costs.
A CDollars 183m (Pounds 89m) modernisation scheme, primarily designed to
cope with environmental problems, would also boost annual zinc output from
about 80,000 to 100,000 tonnes and copper production from 70,000 to 80,000
tonnes, said Mr Tim Wadeson, technical director of Minorco, yesterday.
Minorco, part of the Anglo American Corporation of South Africa, took over
Hudson Bay for USDollars 85 in August. Canada's federal government has
provided a CDollars 25m loan and the provincial government one of CDollars
55m towards the modernisation project.
Mr Wadeson said at a presentation to the Association of Mining Analysts in
London that the scheme was likely to be finished ahead of schedule and under
budget in 1994.
Then Hudson's zinc production costs (including credits for by-product
metals) would be down from 50 cents a lb to 30 cents, making it one of the
world's most competitive producers.
Hudson Bay was spending CDollars 12m a year on exploration near its nine
mines in Manitoba and Saskatchewan and recently more ore had been found at
depth at the Trout Lake mine.
Mr Wadeson said recent exploration work by Minorco's Independence Mining
subsidiary might, 'if we're lucky', result in a new gold mine and associated
plant in Nevada. Independence had lifted annual exploration spending from
USDollars 11.7m to Dollars 15.2m.
Since Minorco acquired Independence for Dollars 705m from Freeport McMoRan
in 1990, total reserves and resources had increased by 40 per cent: to 2.9m
ounces of gold in reserves and 2.7m ounces in resources.
Independence expected to produce 317,218 ounces of gold at a cash cost of
Dollars 229 an ounce in the 1991-92 year to generate revenue of Dollars 357
an ounce. This compared with 304,682 ounces at a cost of Dollars 220 and
revenue per ounce of Dollars 374 in the previous 12 months.
</TEXT>
