FT  03 APR 92 / International Company News: New rescue plan for Forsta
Sparbanken
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SWEDISH government announced a new SKr7.3bn (Dollars 1.2bn) rescue
package for Forsta Sparbanken, the troubled savings bank which was hit by
heavy credit losses in the property and construction sectors last year.
Bankers and Finance Ministry officials have spent the past week in meetings
in order to work out a way of saving Forsta after the bank announced its
credit losses for 1991 were even bigger than originally projected.
Credit losses reached SKr5.7bn instead of the SKr4.5bn which the bank had
forecast in October, and Forsta reported a SKr5.49bn operating loss for the
year.
Its troubles have been complicated by the fact that it is one of the 11
regional savings banks which planned to form a single large savings bank
group this year with the aim of seeking a stock market listing in 1993.
Complications arose because Forsta received an emergency SKr3.8bn loan from
Sparbanksgruppen, the savings bank group which will help form the new
banking group. The loan was guaranteed by government.
According to banking regulations, Forsta could not join the new savings bank
group while still keeping the loan from another part of the new group.
However, yesterday's package resolved Forsta's problems by proposing:
The parts of Forsta's loan portfolio expected to cause major losses will be
put into a separate subsidiary of Forsta and Sparbanken Sverige The
subsidiary will try to dispose of the loan portfolio.
The government has agreed to lend SKr3.8bn to Forsta's owner, a foundation,
which will transfer the loan to Forsta. The funds can later be used to pay
back Sparbanksgruppen's original SKr3.8bn loan. The government loan is
interest-free until the end of 1995, and thereafter carries an interest rate
of 4 per cent.
The 11 savings banks foundations which own Sparbanksgruppen will raise up to
SKr3.5bn in the market. The borrowing will be guaranteed by the government
and can take the form of a bond or loan. Forsta will receive this as an
injection of shareholders' capital.
</TEXT>
