FT  03 APR 92 / UK Company News: Oliver losses jump to Pounds 10.7m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OLIVER GROUP, the shoe retailer which tried unsuccessfully to diversify just
ahead of the recession, yesterday announced pre-tax losses sharply increased
from Pounds 2.68m to Pounds 10.7m due to weakening sales, losses on
disposals and re-organisation costs.
The results were expected and followed a profits warning in January. The
shares fell a further 4p to 55p, compared to last year's high of 126 1/2 p.
Turnover fell to Pounds 84.9m (Pounds 98m) in the year to December 31 as
consumer spending dried up.
There was an trading loss of Pounds 2.95m (profit Pounds 3.48m) as costs
continued to rise, mainly reflecting higher rent reviews.
Mr Ian Oliver, chairman, said that last year was the most difficult in
memory. He announced exceptional losses of Pounds 5.29m to cover falls in
the value of some short-lease shops, losses on property sales and
re-organisation costs.
Losses per share emerged at 39.43p (earnings 9.54p). The company is not
paying a final dividend, although the interim dividend was maintained at
1.07p. Last year's total was 5.82p.
The picture framing division, acquired in 1989, continued to lose money and
was sold last month. This incurred an extraordinary loss of Pounds 768,000
and took total losses for the year to Pounds 10.7m.
The company defended its reserves by revaluing freehold and long leasehold
properties, last valued in 1986. This led to a re-valuation surplus of
Pounds 11.6m, which lifted shareholders' funds slightly to Pounds 42.3m
(Pounds 41.7m).
Oliver also announced that it had bought 21 units from the receiver of
Tandem shoes. All these shops are forecast to trade profitably this year,
the company said.
