<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / London Stock Exchange: Poll news leaves Footsie at 1992 low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVIDENCE from opinion polls that Labour has established a significant lead
over the Conservative party triggered a predictable, but nevertheless heavy,
slide in UK share prices, which closed at their lowest levels so far this
year. The falls compounded a difficult day in international stock markets
which saw another hefty fall on the Tokyo market and a poor showing by Wall
Street during the afternoon.
The FT-SE 100-share Index plunged through the 2,400 level but later rallied
to close well above the day's worst with a net fall of 31.5 at 2,408.6.
The steep drop in share prices accompanied big falls in the gilt-edged
market and a rise in the three-month interbank rate as markets pondered the
chances of an increase in UK interest rates - currently at 10 1/2 per cent -
after next Thursday's general election.
The slide in equities took place during the busiest trading session on the
stock market this year. Seaq turnover totalled 701.6m shares, compared with
a previous high of 606.1m recorded on February 27. Yesterday's figure,
however, was given a substantial boost by a series of big placings and at
least six mostly small-size programme trades.
Marketmakers, most of which were thought to be carrying long positions, took
evasive action from the outset, chopping prices back to head off any
attempted sizeable selling. The Footsie opened 56 points down at 2,384.1,
subsequently proving to be the day's lowest, and quickly embarked on a
determined rally as a number of institutions moved in to pick up cheap
stock.
Dealers said 2,400 had been the trigger for a flurry of support. The buying
petered out mid-morning, however, with the index standing 26.7 off. The
afternoon session proved equally difficult for traders, with a weak Wall
Street opening prompting fresh bouts of selling of leading UK stocks.
Some senior marketmakers were dismayed at the latest turn of events. One
said the market had to absorb big lines of stock following heavy selling by
UK institutions. 'The market has been spooked and it looks odds on a Labour
administration,' said one. 'The mood is dreadful and there is still plenty
of downside. I just hope the overseas funds do not start selling,' he added.
Other dealers, however, said they had recorded more big institutional buy
trades than sales. 'There was an element of panic but it seems the market
has found a pretty good trading level,' was one view.
The drama of a falling market tended to mask some hefty share placings and a
series of corporate events. United Newspapers was the most heavily traded
stock as bought deal specialist Smith New Court, in tandem with Cazenove,
swooped to purchase the 8.7 per cent stake of some 17.25m shares held by Mr
Conrad Black, the Canadian entrepreneur, and placed the shares in the
market, taking a 4p a share turn in the process.
Smith also bought and sold a block of 3.5m shares in Lasmo, the oil group,
making a profit of 3p a share.
Utilities, retailers and property and building issues, undermined by fears
of a rise in interest rates, were among the worst affected areas.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 40
</PAGE>
</DOC>
