<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / International Company News: O&amp;Y move to pay off overdue debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; York, the cash-strapped Canadian property developer, is expected
to raise several hundred million dollars over the next few days to help meet
overdue debt obligations.
The Toronto-based company was expected to announce late yesterday or today
that GW Utilities, its 89 per cent owned subsidiary, would immediately
provide O&amp;Y with a short-term loan pending the receipt of CDollars 158m
(USDollars 132.7m) in special dividends from GWU on April 14.
The dividends are being financed from GWU's sale last month of its
controlling interest in Interprovincial PipeLine, a large oil pipeline
operator, for CDollars 655m.
GWU is itself arranging a substantial loan secured by the second instalment
from the Interprovincial sale, totalling CDollars 277m, which is only due to
be paid by buyers of the shares in March 1993. This receivables financing
will, in effect, give GWU immediate access to the full proceeds of the
Interprovincial sale.
In addition, O&amp;Y is understood to be within days of concluding the sale of
Exchange Tower, a Toronto building which houses its own head office and the
Toronto Stock Exchange.
O&amp;Y is due to present an interim plan for the restructuring of its estimated
CDollars 20bn debt to its creditors in Toronto on April 6.
A report by RBC Dominion Securities, Canada's biggest securities firm, has
put O&amp;Y's exposure to Canadian banks at CDollars 2.6bn, which is somewhat
higher than earlier estimates.
Proceeds from the Exchange Tower sale and the GWU loan will be used to
retire two O&amp;Y CP programmes.
Repayments under these programmes have come to a virtual halt since O&amp;Y
revealed on March 22 that it was suffering a liquidity crisis. The amount of
commercial paper outstanding remains at about CDollars 380m.
O&amp;Y has gained further breathing space thanks to what is described as an
'informal' standstill agreement with a group of financial institutions on a
CDollars 450m loan to finance construction of the 68-storey Scotia Plaza
complex in downtown Toronto.
O&amp;Y failed to make a principal payment on the loan due on March 31.
The lenders refused O&amp;Y's request for a one-year rollover, but a source
close to the company said they had agreed not to take precipitate action to
enforce repayment.
Mr Michael Goldberg, Dominion Securities' banking analyst, said yesterday
that his figures of the banks' loans to O&amp;Y were based on 'educated
estimates'.
Mr Goldberg puts the exposure of Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, O&amp;Y's
biggest creditor, at CDollars 1.1bn, which is higher than other estimates
published so far.
Royal Bank of Canada's exposure is estimated at CDollars 700m, Bank of Nova
Scotia at CDollars 450m, Bank of Montreal at CDollars 200m and National Bank
at CDollars 150m.
The sixth Canadian bank, Toronto-Dominion, last week said that it has no
direct exposure to O&amp;Y.
</TEXT>
