<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Daily Telegraph listing proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX and BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR CONRAD Black, the Can-adian proprietor of the Daily Telegraph, yesterday
announced he was considering a stock exchange listing for the UK newspaper
group in June 'barring a market over-reaction' to the outcome of the UK
election.
He also announced the sale of his 8.8 per cent stake in United Newspapers,
publishers of the Daily Express.
The proposed flotation would require the Hollinger Group, the international
media group which is Mr Black's main holding company, to reduce its holding
from 83 per cent to 70 per cent. A minority of the shares is held by
directors and former owners of the Telegraph newspapers.
The Telegraph newspapers have just announced pre-tax profits for 1991 of
Pounds 40.5m on turnover of Pounds 219m, compared with profits of Pounds
38.5m the year before, on turnover of Pounds 222m.
Mr Joe Cooke, managing director of the Daily Telegraph, said the proposed
flotation and the sale of the United Newspapers stake did not indicate
Hollinger was short of money: 'It is more in the way of building up a war
chest.'
Hollinger Group sold the 17.25m United Newspapers shares to brokers Smith
New Court and Cazenove, who placed them with several dozen institutions at
350p a share, raising Pounds 60.4m.
United Newspapers shares yesterday slipped by 13p to 360p.
The average price paid by Hollinger in building the stake in July and August
1989 is believed to be about 458p, implying a loss on the shares of Pounds
18.6m. This does not include the cost of financing the investment or
dividends received.
Mr Jack Boultbee, vice-president for finance at Hollinger's head office in
Toronto, said yesterday there was 'no particular need' for the company to
raise money, but that 'there's a lot of sense in paying down debt right now
whether or not we take on anything else', writes Bernard Simon in Toronto.
He said Hollinger gave a 'soft commitment' to spin off some of its interest
in the Telegraph at the time of its original investment. He added that the
company expects to raise 'at least' CDollars 120m (Pounds 58.4m) by reducing
its stake from 83 per cent to 70 per cent, double what it paid for its
original 58 per cent stake in the company.
</TEXT>
