<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Caution dominates steadier Tokyo market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN BUTLER and EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BARGAIN HUNTERS helped to steady the Tokyo stock market in initial trading
early today, after the sharp drop yesterday despite a cut in the official
discount rate.
But sentiment remained predominantly cautious as Japan weighed the likely
impact of the rate cut and of the emergency package announced by the
government on Tuesday to try to stimulate the economy.
The Nikkei average was up 200 points in early trading. The steadier tone
came after the Nikkei plunged 764.16 to close at 18,581.79 in the previous
day's trading.
It was the first time since early 1987 that the market had slid through the
19,000-level. The fall was partly because investors who had bought shares
last autumn liquidated positions into a market with no buyers in sight.
Mr Yasushi Mieno, governor of the Bank of Japan, the central bank, yesterday
left no doubt that the official discount rate, lowered by 0.75 points to
3.75 per cent, had hit bottom, at least for the time being.
He said monetary policy was limited in its ability to stimulate the economy.
He described the rate cut as the final phase of credit easing, and said the
level was low by historical standards.
At the same time, Mr Mieno expressed confidence that the process of reducing
excess manufacturing inventories would continue. A build-up of unsold
inventories has caused manufacturing companies to cut output and has slowed
the pace of the economy. Mr Mieno said, however, that the interest rate cut,
combined with the government's financial package, would restore the economy
to a path of stable expansion.
The measures failed to coax investors in a large way back into the market
immediately. Life assurers, which were leading buyers of equities in the
late 1980s, have started to move from stock investments and into direct
corporate lending. The flow of money into investment trusts has also dried
up as individual investors have grown weary of the scandal-tainted market.
Investors with funds have been staying on the sidelines, convinced the
market may fall further. Analysts, nonetheless, said the decline would have
little effect on the broader economy.
'We don't think it will have any economic implications except for
confidence,' said Mr Paul Summerville, economist at Jardine Fleming. 'The
sources of growth in the Japanese economy are less dependent on the stock
market than in the last cycle.'
Ms Rie Ota, analyst at Baring Securities, said the decline in the market had
contributed to an erosion of capital asset ratios at Japan's commercial and
long-term credit banks.
The rate cut and the financial package were broadly welcomed by industrial
leaders. Mr Takeshi Nagano, president of the Japan Federation of Employers'
Associations, praised the timing. Mr Keizo Saji, chairman of the Osaka
Chamber of Commerce and Industry, however, said the rate cut by itself was
insufficient, and called for lower taxes.
Silver lining, Page 28
Bond market report, Page 29
World stocks, Page 37
</TEXT>
