<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Arts: Edinburgh Festival
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
There are four themes running through this year's Edinburgh Festival, the
first under the stewardship of Brian McMaster, formerly controller of the
Welsh National Opera.
The most obvious is the music of Tchaikovsky. A retrospective embraces 30
events. The highlights are a concert performance of his rarely staged opera
The Oprichnik, by Scottish Opera on August 20; his Cantata Moscow on
September 3; and a re-creation of his original opera and ballet double-bill
Yolanta and The Nutcracker from August 26-29.
Another theme is a series of five concerts featuring music by Scottish
composers, including the Scottish premiere of James McMillan's Percussion
Concerto performed by Evelyn Glennie.
Drama includes retrospectives devoted to Harley Granville Barker, including
his three major works, The Voysey Inheritance, The Madras House and His
Majesty, and to the Glasgow-born playwright C. P. Taylor. The National
Theatre brings Lope de Vega's Fuente Ovejuna.
Details from Festival Office, 21 Market Street, Edinburgh EH1 1BW (Tel: 031
226 4001).
</TEXT>
