<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Record price made for Japanese sword: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHRISTIE'S sold in New York on Tuesday part of the superb collection of
Japanese swords and sword fittings assembled by the late Walter A. Compton.
The 399 lots fetched Dollars 7.99m (Pounds 4.6m), a record for an auction of
Japanese work.
Swords were revered as religious symbols by the Japanese, and a samurai
regarded his blade as far more valuable than land or gold. The top price was
Dollars 418,000, a record for a sword. It was paid by a private European
collector for a Fukuoka Ichimonji tachi, or long sword for mounted warriors.
It was forged in the 13th century and signed Ichi.
A Japanese dealer acquired a Soshu Ichimonji tachi, signed Sukezane, and
made in about 1250, for Dollars 374,000. A Japanese private buyer paid
Dollars 341,000 for an Osaka Inoue katana, a short blade used in fighting on
foot, signed Inoue Shinkai and dated 1677. All three prices were comfortably
above forecast. A Shinshinto Musashi tachi of about 1850, which was
estimated at Dollars 25,000, sold for Dollars 242,000.
Compton started building one of the finest sword collections in 1963.
Christie's plans two more sales of the swords and should exceed its Dollars
20m estimate for the 1,000 lots.
Sotheby's in London sold second-division Old Master paintings with some
success. The morning session raised Pounds 1.5m with less than 13 per cent
unsold. A portrait of two children attributed to Moroni sold to a Swiss
collector for Pounds 187,000, against an estimate of Pounds 30,000 to Pounds
40,000.
</TEXT>
