   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PRESCOTT, shadow transport secretary, yesterday promised spending of
Pounds 41m over the first two years of a Labour government to upgrade rail
services on the west coast main line, Paul Cheeseright writes. The line runs
between London Euston and Glasgow through the west Midlands and Lancashire.
He said in Derby that two prototype trains would be ordered immediately
after the election, and that their performance would be checked by
independent design controllers. British Rail would be invited to renew the
track and signalling and a training programme would be started to increase
the pool of electrical engineers.
Mr Prescott said the programme would 'lead to high-speed rail links for
passengers and freight before the end of the century'. He added that Labour
would modernise railways, not privatise them.
