<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / A bumpy ride on a firmer track: The outlook for
rolling-stock maker Brel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 6,500 workers at Brel, the largest UK railway rolling-stock maker, may
be relieved that the troubled company is coming under the majority control
of Asea Brown Boveri - but they may be in for a bumpy ride.
By purchasing the 40 per cent stake in Brel held by Trafalgar House, the
Swiss-Swedish company ABB has at least resolved part of the uncertainty over
Brel.
Ownership of Brel now looks secure, with Europe's largest electrical
engineering group holding 80 per cent and managers and employees sharing the
rest.
But Brel now faces the prospect of becoming a much more integrated part of
ABB, and that is where the question marks remain.
The deal might open the way for Brel to benefit from closer co-operation
with ABB and share in work on overseas orders. Even so, Mr Bo Sodersten,
installed as chief executive by ABB and Trafalgar House six months ago to
revamp Brel's badly-organised management structure, stresses this will
depend on Brel's continuing efforts to improve competitiveness.
At the same time, though, the share purchase brings Brel closer to a big ABB
division, transport, which is not exactly the star in the multinational's
firmament.
In Stockholm last month Mr Percy Barnevik, ABB's hard-driving president,
made clear that he remained dissatisfied with the profitability of a
division with 12,000 employees, excellent technology and rising orders, but
also profits that were low in 1990 and lower still last year.
ABB's transport business, like most of the rest of Europe's rail equipment
sector, is struggling to emerge from its fragmented, inefficient and
nationally-based past into a pan-European market where the old cosy
'cost-plus' relationships between suppliers and railway companies are
loosening.
ABB has been a key factor in the resultant restructuring, with nine
acquisitions across Europe since 1988. This helped boost its transportation
revenues from Dollars 1.31bn (Pounds 743m) in 1990 to Dollars 1.9bn last
year, but profits remain depressed.
Mr Barnevik says, however, the mid and long-term external outlook is bright,
with the 'comeback' of railways in Europe and Asian expansion plans offering
tempting prospects for well-organised European suppliers.
Brel's future could benefit from the expected world growth in rolling-stock
sales. Mr Sodersten says it will be 'much easier to find really good areas
of co-operation now that ABB has 80 per cent of the company'.
Brel has a solid repair and overhaul business at Crewe, where Mr Sodersten
has had little need to wield the hatchet. Its problem has mainly been that
of management, and particularly in its new construction business at York and
Derby.
Mr Richard Hope, consultant editor of Railway Gazette International, says:
'That's what brought them to grief. They have not been organised in getting
their components suppliers and subcontractors lined up.'
Mr Sodersten has had to reorganise management of the new construction
division, and across Brel as a whole 1,000 jobs have gone since he took
charge. He is pleased with what has been achieved, but admits more needs to
be done.
While the restructuring under Mr Sodersten continues, the short-term key to
Brel's survival, let alone prosperity, is work from the UK. That is why
observers believe this week's settlement of an acrimonious dispute with
British Rail over the cost of modifications to 447 class-158 coaches is
significant.
While not directly linked, it looks like smoothing the path for the award by
BR in the next few days of a Pounds 130m order for 188 coaches for Network
SouthEast.
Capturing such orders, and sharing in ABB's transportation growth, will be
crucial in deciding any further job cuts at Brel.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-15144</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDBBKAFHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920402
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / British Coal profit higher than last year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL is to announce record profits for the second successive year,
the corporation said yesterday. Profits will be even higher than last year,
when the corporation made Pounds 78m, its first profit for 15 years.
The corporation also announced its biggest increase in productivity, which
rose from an average of 4.7 tonnes per manshift last year to 5.3 tonnes this
year. British Coal also set a new productivity target of 7.5 tonnes per
manshift within two years.
Mr Neil Clarke, chairman, said: 'It's quite clear British Coal has made
another tremendous leap forward in terms of efficiency'.
Last year, 15 pits closed, but the corporation still produced 70.5m tonnes
of coal, just 1m tonnes less than the year before.
The corporation's improved record will be an important bargaining counter
for British Coal as it negotiates important new contracts to sell coal to
the electricity generators, National Power and PowerGen, who buy about 80
per cent of the corporation's coal.
