<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Tube line in Docklands is wins support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday expressed support for extending London Underground's
Jubilee Line to Docklands. But it stopped short of offering to provide funds
if Olympia &amp; York, the property developer, failed to provide its share of
the finance.
O&amp;Y agreed under a proposal announced by the Department of Transport in 1989
to contribute Pounds 400m to the cost of the Pounds 1.3bn project, with the
rest coming from the government. There is also thought to be a smaller
contribution due from British Gas.
Ms Joan Ruddock, a shadow transport minister, said: 'We are not seeking any
variation of the proposals. The plan (for the extension) is there ready to
start. We want O&amp;Y to come up with the money.'
O&amp;Y, which is holding debt-restructuring talks with its banks, was
originally expected to pay Pounds 40m towards the project on Tuesday.
However, the Department of Transport has said that if the agreement with O&amp;Y
about its contribution to the project's costs is not concluded before the
election, the first payment will become due on the day the agreement is
signed. Ms Ruddock declined to be drawn on reports that O&amp;Y and its banks
might seek to reduce their contribution - a move that would almost certainly
shift the onus to the Treasury.
'We still expect Olympia &amp; York or its bankers and British Gas to honour
their financial commitments to this scheme,' she said. 'Clearly we want to
see whatever is on offer and see how best the contract can be drawn up.' If
O&amp;Y carried out its 'moral obligation' and came up with its share, there was
'no reason why the extension should not go ahead within the original
timetable'.
Last week Mr Wilfred Newton, chairman of London Transport, wrote to Sir
Jeremy Morse, chairman of Lloyds Bank - which is co-ordinating the UK
restructuring of O&amp;Y - saying that O&amp;Y's obligations on the Jubilee Line
should be met. 'You will, of course, be aware of the crucial importance of
the Jubilee Line extension to the medium and long- term fortunes of Olympia
&amp; York's development at Canary Wharf,' he wrote.
Labour hopes O&amp;Y and its bankers will back the project because of the risk
that failure to do so might jeopardise Canary Wharf.
</TEXT>
