<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Decline in housing index slows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSE PRICES fell in February for the fourth successive month, the latest
index published by Nationwide Building Society shows. But the fact that
February's decline was only 0.2 per cent has kindled hopes of a recovery.
In each of the previous three months house prices fell by well over 1
percentage point, and prices have fallen in nine of the past 12 months.
Mr David Gilchrist, general manager of Halifax Building Society, the largest
UK mortgage lender, said the figures suggested that the housing market might
have bottomed out after three years. 'We think that the market is on the
turn and this should be clearly seen this spring,' he added.
Mr Peter Munday, Nationwide's divisional director, said: 'March is
traditionally a busy time in the housing market, and early in the month we
were seeing strong signs of increased activity.' But he added that many
people might be delaying buying until after the election.
Last month's slight fall compares with an 0.7 per cent rise in house prices
in March last year. The average UK house price now stands at Pounds 55,193,
4.9 per cent lower than a year ago.
