<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / German challenge to Farnborough
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GERMAN aerospace industry is challenging Britain by staging in June its
first air show in Berlin since the Second World War. It will be only three
months before the Farnborough air show at the beginning of September.
The challenge reflects Germany's ambitions for its aerospace industry, which
has been regrouped around Daimler-Benz, the industrial group. Sir Barry
Duxbury, the director of the Society of British Aerospace Companies, the
organiser of Farnborough, conceded yesterday that the German move was
increasing the competition in the world of air shows.
But he said he was confident Farnborough would retain its lead and that the
show this year would be a success in spite of the recession, the decline in
the airline industry and the cuts in the defence industry.
Farnborough and Paris are the leading international air shows and alternate
every other year. The society and its French equivalent are determined to
maintain the current standing of their respective shows.
</TEXT>
