<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Howard Davies to be CBI chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry is expected to announce next week the
appointment of Mr Howard Davies, controller of the Audit Commission, as its
new director-general.
He will replace Sir John Banham, who also was controller of the Audit
Commission, the local-government watchdog, before becoming director-general
of the CBI in 1987.
The CBI said there had been 'a great deal of speculation' about the post,
which had attracted more than 100 applicants. It added that an announcement
was expected on election day, when the organisation's ruling council meets.
The choice of a CBI director-general is the responsibility of Sir Brian
Corby, the organisation's retiring president. He is to be replaced by Sir
Michael Angus, chairman of Unilever.
Mr Davies has apparently been chosen because of his political contacts and
organisational experience. He spent a period at the Treasury while on
secondment from McKinsey, the management consultants, as an advisor to Mr
Nigel Lawson when he was chancellor. He was appointed controller of the
Audit Commission after Sir John's departure.
Observer, Page 18
</TEXT>
