<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Lamont optimism on recovery finds glimmer of support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT, the chancellor, said yesterday Britain's economic recovery
may be under way. He was rewarded by tentative evidence of improved business
conditions from parts of industry.
Mr Lamont said on the BBC's Today programme: 'It may be that when the
statistics are compiled that we will see that recovery has already started.'
Hours later his claim gained some support from a survey of UK purchasing
managers and signs of greater optimism in the lighting industry. A report
from 3i, the venture capital group, and Cranfield School of Management said
smaller UK businesses were more hopeful than their continental counterparts
that profits would improve this year.
The Institute of Purchasing and Supply reported that its purchasing
managers' index rose to 54.1 per cent last month from 50.8 per cent in
February and 48.1 per cent in December last year. It said that suggested
'significant economic growth is under way in the manufacturing economy'.
The Lighting Industry Federation, which represents companies with total
annual turnover of Pounds 650m and 17,000 employees, said its latest monthly
trends inquiry pointed to a recovery in orders since January with nearly
half the companies polled expecting to increase output in the next four
months.
Neither of these indicators has a known track record, however, although one
economist said they might be 'straws in the wind'. The purchasing managers'
survey, which is based on techniques developed in the US, started in July
last year.
The latest Treasury survey of independent economic forecasts, published
yesterday, found that the average expectation of growth this year fell to 1
per cent in March from 1.2 per cent in February.
Meanwhile, a bleak analysis of economic developments from Mr Peter
Warburton, the monetarist chief economist of Robert Fleming Securities,
warned that there is little chance of growth without a fall in interest
rates and a devaluation of sterling in the European exchange rate mechanism.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
