<DOCNO>FT922-15154</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDBBKAE7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920402
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Unions reject chemical industry's 4% offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH and CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS representing 20,000 chemical process workers have rejected an offer
by employers which would lead to minimum pay rates rising about 4 per cent.
The employers agreed to provide 3.76 per cent in new money. Consolidation of
other payments would lead to a 4.16 per cent rise in the minimum rate,
taking it to Pounds 3.88 an hour.
Negotiating through the Chemical Industries Association, the employers
rejected union claims for a cut in the 39-hour week and an increase in
holidays. They agreed to establish a group to look at equal opportunities.
Increases in minimum rates do not necessarily lead to comparable increases
for all workers as the industry practices two-tier bargaining through which
local negotiations supplement national talks.
Until recently most companies followed the percentage rise pattern set by
the national talks. The association believes there has been more variation
during the recession. RMT, Britain's largest rail union, is likely today to
reject British Rail's 4 per cent pay offer for 100,000 staff.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
