<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Insurance ruling
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE rights of policyholders to have insurance claims paid even if their
insurers go out of business could be limited by a Commercial Court ruling
yesterday.
The ruling came in a case involving three policyholders of subsidiaries of
London United Investments, which went into administration in 1990.
Under the Policyholders Protection Act of 1975 policyholders can claim a sum
equal to 90 per cent of claims from insurance companies which have gone into
liquidation.
Mr Justice Webster ruled that contingent liabilities - where an event giving
rise to a claim has occurred but the amount due has still to be determined -
are excluded from protection under the act.
</TEXT>
