<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Lobbyists' pressure proves positive in EC: British
organisations beating their rivals to the policymakers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH organisations are rapidly learning how to lobby Brussels. In the
process, they are even beating French and German rivals in the race to the
policymakers, according to Mr Jeremy Richardson, director of the European
Public Policy Institute based at Warwick University.
'British groups, used to a tradition of close and informal relationships
with civil servants, are rather adept at influencing policymaking in
Brussels and indeed are regarded as good Europeans,' says Mr Richardson.
His conclusions find support among those involved. 'The British operation
nowadays tends to be quite sophisticated compared with the French and
Germans,' says the Brussels office of Hill &amp; Knowlton, the US public
relations company.
Mrs Edith Cresson, before she became French prime minister, called on French
companies to be more assertive in dealing with Brussels directly, rather
than relying on l'etat, according to Mr Richardson.
By contrast, the British Textiles Confederation is lobbying Brussels
directly to prevent German carpet quality standards, based on springiness,
taking precedence over their UK equivalent, based on comfort and durability.
The chemicals sector, too, has taken the battle to Brussels. Mr Jonathan
Peel, executive director of EC and government relations at the UK Chemicals
Industries Association, says: 'We have become much more active in Brussels
in the last two or three years because more of the weighty decisions are
being made there.'
Britain's parliamentary constituency system has bred lobbying into UK
companies, says Mr Peel. 'There isn't the same sense of that in France or
Germany'.
The EC patchwork means that UK companies have found themselves on familiar
ground when lobbying. There are 23 directorates-general, each divided into a
number of policy units. The commission is headed by 17 commissioners, each
of whom has an entourage to screen those seeking access to the commissioner.
</TEXT>
