<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Election 1992: Checking out the blue-rinse brigade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S vote-seeking pol-iticians were yesterday given a comprehensive
thumbs-down by that driving force in any election, the blue-rinse brigade of
Sainsbury shoppers.
Trolley-pushing voters in six safe southern Tory seats - Carshalton, Sutton,
Epsom, Horsham, Worthing and Hove - granted John Major a narrow vote of
confidence.
In an exclusive FT poll of blue-clad middle-aged lady shoppers outside
Sainsbury stores there was one overwhelming message to the politicians: head
for the electoral checkout and get it all over with as quickly as possible.
Out of the small but scientifically chosen sample of women shoppers wearing
blue coats or pullovers - two in each constituency - five said they would
vote Conservative, two each gave their allegiance to Labour, the Greens and
the Liberal Democrats, with one saying she would abstain.
Outside Sainsbury, Wallington, in the Carshalton constituency (majority:
14,409), Mrs Mary Cunningham in a bright-blue coat said she was a
traditional Conservative but had hesitated in making up her mind this time
before being pushed back to the Tory camp by fury over Labour's health
broadcast. 'I'd like to punch Neil Kinnock on the nose,' she said.
In North Cheam, in the Sutton constituency (majority: 15,718), Mrs
Jacqueline Brown said she would vote Liberal. 'None of them are coming over
very well.' Mrs Ida Cass, with a mauve tint to her hair, said she was Green
'because of what they're trying to do for the world'.
In Epsom (majority: 20,761) Mrs Evelyn R, a lifelong Tory in a blue anorak,
said that for the first time she would not be voting. She was 'disgusted' by
the Tory performance. 'Education, employment - you name it, they've messed
it up.' She did not want her name quoted because Tory friends would think
she was 'a renegade'.
In Horsham (majority 23,907) Mrs Doris Whitehead said she would opt for the
Tories but without enthusiasm. So would Mrs Dora Silver 'I'm sick to death
of the politicians on TV. They go on and on and on,' she said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
