FT  02 APR 92 / Election 1992: Voters seek effective third party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS MANY as 53 per cent of voters would be likely to support the Liberal
Democrats if they thought the party could win a majority, according to
today's Daily Telegraph/ Gallup poll.
The figure falls to 44 per cent if the party were likely to hold the balance
of power. Only 20.5 per cent of respondents said they would vote Lib Dem if
there was an election tomorrow.
The survey also gives further evidence of Labour's improved ratings for
economic competence: 38 per cent said they felt the party could best handle
Britain's economic difficulties, against 44 per cent for the Conservatives
and 31 per cent before the campaign.
Meanwhile, the latest ICM poll for The Guardian, published yesterday, points
to a fall-off in Conservative support among women, the paper says today.
The survey, which gave Labour a four-point lead overall, put the party three
points ahead among female voters.
This reversed the position in a poll published on March 17 which suggested
that women favoured the Tories by a margin of three points.
