<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Election 1992: Major tries to win the undecided
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN APPEAL to the uncommitted to 'come and join us' came yesterday from Mr
John Major as he led the Tories' attempt to win over floating voters in the
final week of the campaign.
The Tories believe that there are some 10m people who have not yet decided
how to vote - a larger proportion of the electorate than is usual this close
to polling day.
Speaking at a party rally near Bath, Mr Major said: 'This is no time to be a
'don't know'. This is a time to fight for a positive future for our
country.'
He spelt out his aims for a Britain in which people had the incentive to
work harder and create resources for better public services, and urged those
who shared that vision to talk to people who were still uncertain. 'None of
us can afford to stay on the sidelines. What is at stake is the future of
Britain,' he said.
Beyond presenting the positive Tory vision, however, Mr Major sounded a
warning about what a Labour government would mean. He highlighted the choice
between the Conservatives and the other parties on devolution, defence and
Britain's role in Europe.
Earlier on a visit to Bath, the marginal seat where party chairman Mr Chris
Patten is under pressure from the Liberal Democrats, Mr Major was hit by an
egg thrown from a crowd of demonstrators.
Mr Christopher Chope, the roads minister, was struck in the face while
campaigning in his Southampton Itchen constituency last night. Police were
called as he was taken to a nearby house for first aid.
</TEXT>
