<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Election 1992: No slackening, orders confident Kinnock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NEIL Kinnock last night launched the final phase of his general election
campaign with a confident prediction of victory at the largest political
rally in Britain since the second world war.
At a Pounds 150,000 Labour extravaganza in Sheffield, Mr Kinnock told 10,000
supporters: 'In nine days' time Britain is going to have a Labour
government.'
The party would win because 'people know we will govern as we have
campaigned - strongly, positively, looking to the future.'
By contrast, the Conservative government was portrayed as a spent force:
'They have no vitality and they are rapidly losing the remnants of their
integrity.'
Senior party figures echoed his confidence that the Conservatives would be
defeated on April 9. Despite last night's opinion polls, strategists said
there was overwhelming evidence that Labour support had been firmly
established above 40 per cent. That would be enough to deprive Mr John Major
of his majority.
But Mr Kinnock has warned colleagues that the last 48 hours of the campaign
will be crucial in determining whether Labour secures an overall majority.
He has ordered that there should be no slackening in the disciplined
campaigning which has given his party the lead.
Last night's rally was designed to reinforce the party's confident image and
lift the morale of its supporters as it enters the final days of
campaigning.
Framed by giant video screens, Mr Kinnock sought to reinforce his image as
prime minister-in-waiting with a dismissive attack on the Conservatives'
'negative' campaigning.
While Mr John Major traded in 'sour insults', Labour would 'carry on
fighting for the British people.'
Setting Labour's task as healing the divisions wrought by 13 years of
Conservative government, Mr Kinnock signalled that education, health,
housing and social welfare would be at the centre of his campaign until
polling day.
He accused the Conservatives of seeking the end of 'free schooling' and the
privatisation of the National Health Service. In a scathing reference to Mr
Major's 'soapbox' campaigning he said: 'What's at issue in this election is
not the soapboxes that people stand on. It's the cardboard boxes that people
live in.'
Mr Kinnock said Labour's alternative prospectus for the economy and social
provision would be based on the experience of successful competitor
countries.
That meant support for investment and innovation and an understanding that
it was essential for a modern government 'to support research, to improve
the transport system, to foster long-term industrial development, and to
make a continual commitment to raising standards of skill.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
