<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Mitterrand prolongs uncertainty on Cresson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Mitterrand yesterday appeared to be having second thoughts over
the dismissal of Mrs Edith Cresson as French prime minister.
Her removal had previously been regarded as virtually inevitable after the
disastrous setback suffered by the government in the recent round of local
elections.
Le Monde yesterday openly aired the possibility that President Mitterrand
might be in the process of changing his mind over whether to replace Mrs
Cresson. But, Mr Jean Auroux, parliamentary leader of the Socialist Party,
predicted that a new government of some kind would be formed within the next
24 hours.
For the third day running, the President conducted intensive consultations
with friends and associates on the lessons to be drawn from the regional and
departmental elections, in which the Socialists suffered humiliating
defeats.
Mrs Cresson was again summoned to the Elysee Palace for talks, but when she
returned to her office at the Hotel Matignon, it appeared nothing had been
settled.
A broadcaster who accompanied her on Tuesday to the Hanover trade fair said
Mrs Cresson had privately vented her bitterness against the party, accusing
the Socialist leader, Mr Laurent Fabius, and the finance minister, Mr Pierre
Beregovoy, of having sabotaged her premiership.
If President Mitterrand were to ask Mrs Cresson to stay on, she is believed
to have told him that she would want a far-reaching cabinet reshuffle that
would include the removal of many of the barons of the Socialist Party,
known colloquially as 'les elephants'.
The depth of the crisis precipitated by the regional election results also
appears to have brought to the surface antagonisms between leading members
of the Socialist Party, as well as differences over the right policy choices
to respond to the popular vote.
President Mitterrand's delay in making up his mind does not prove that he
has decided to keep Mrs Cresson, nor that he has decided against any of the
other candidates. But he is evidently determined to take all the time he
needs before making up his mind on such a critical choice at such a critical
time, since this is probably the last change of government he can make
before next year's general elections.
Officials at the Elysee Palace said that Mr Mitterrand was mainly
preoccupied in thinking about how the government should best change its
policies in response to the swingeing disavowal of the electorate. They
suggested that the President's strategic decisions in adopting new policies
were more important than the choice of a prime minister. Long delays in the
lead-up to an important decision have been frequent in Mr Mitterrand's
career. In 1983, he hesitated for nine days over whether to dismiss Mr
Pierre Mauroy, before finally asking him to stay on.
Yesterday, there were conflicting signals from the camps of the contending
candidates for prime minister. Some of Mrs Cresson's staff indicated that
she might, after all, stay in office, with one official saying: 'We shall
not leave until the crocuses are completely out. The work goes on.'
However, Mr Beregovoy, widely tipped as the favourite to succeed Mrs
Cresson, was reported to be busily engaged in taking soundings with possible
members of a new cabinet.
However, political sources said some senior party barons had launched a
counter-offensive in favour of the European Commission president, Mr Jacques
Delors - despite the fact that Mr Delors has appeared to rule himself out of
the race. They argue that Mr Beregovoy would not be able to rally support
behind the Socialists, who fell to a mere 18.3 per cent in the regional
elections.
See World Stockmarkets
</TEXT>
