<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Shares fall on prospect of Labour win
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARE PRICES in London fell sharply yesterday as investors came to terms
with opinion polls showing the Labour party with a clear lead.
The polls were the main factor driving the FT-SE 100 index of leading shares
down 31.5 to close at 2,408.6. Prices of government gilt-edged securities
fell too, closing nearly a point down.
Mr Robin Aspinall, an economist at Schroders, the merchant bank, said: 'Last
week six out of 10 people in the City thought the Tories would probably win
the election. Now it's six out of 10 who believe a Labour victory is
possible. The City doesn't like the idea of a Labour government and the
nervousness we've seen is the result.'
Yesterday's drop in the FT-SE index means the index has lost nearly 170
points since Budget day on March 10. The jitters also forced up rates in the
London money market, indicating a perception that if Labour wins it might
increase base rates.
Relatively few investors shifted funds out of sterling yesterday. The fall
in the pound against the D-Mark was just half a pfennig. The pound closed in
London at DM2.85, 10 pfennigs below its DM2.95 central rate in the European
exchange rate mechanism (ERM).
The market's worries had their effect on the key three-month interbank rate,
at which banks lend among themselves. It climbed  3/8 of a point, to close
at about 11 1/4 per cent. That pointed to an increase soon in base rates -
which have been held at 10 1/2 per cent for nearly seven months.
Mr John Shepperd, an economist at SG Warburg Securities, said: 'The markets
are looking to a Labour victory, and many people are taking Mr John Smith
(Labour's shadow chancellor) on his word that he will not devalue the pound
in the ERM. But there is also a belief that as soon as Labour takes office,
investors will test his resolve on this point, and sell sterling. On this
basis, to keep the pound in its band, base rates will have to rise.'
Mr Ken De La Salle, head of foreign exchange at National Westminster Bank,
said another reason for nervousness was the size of the public sector
borrowing requirement, which the Treasury says will be Pounds 28bn in the
government's financial year.' To fund this, base rates might rise.
irrespective of who forms the next government.'
