<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Unpaid government bills stall Civil Service headhunters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT appeared to have egg on its face yesterday after the Cabinet
Office admitted that late payment of bills by government departments had
caused cash flow problems at a hived-off agency which selects high fliers
for the Civil Service.
About 30 business people and public figures who help in the selection
process have been told that payment of their fees has been delayed. A letter
to them from the Civil Service commissioner blames cash flow problems at
Recruitment and Assessment Services (RAS), which recruits under contract to
government departments and agencies.
'It appears that the Cabinet Office is informing a cross-section of the
establishment that the much-vaunted Civil Service financial and accounting
reforms don't work as well as they are supposed to,' said one recipient of
the letter.
The Cabinet Office said last night that all outstanding fees would be paid
by Friday. Some of the payments are for work done at the end of January.
The delays will be embarrassing for ministers who have condemned the late
payment of small businesses by large companies. In his Budget speech last
month, Mr Norman Lamont described the practice of boosting cash flow by
delaying payments as 'wholly deplorable'.
Government departments, he said, had a good record for paying their own
bills on time and the government hoped their example would be followed by
private sector companies.
The delays reveal increasing financial problems at one of the government's
executive agencies, on the day that 15 new ones were launched. RAS looks set
to make an Pounds 800,000 loss in its first year, against the government's
target of recovering all its costs in full.
Income at RAS has been depressed by reduced recruitment to the Civil
Service. RAS has also lost business from departments which have taken
advantage of rules introduced in April 1991 allowing them to do their own
recruitment.
</TEXT>
