FT  02 APR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When the state executes people for murder ('Pre-meditated killing is wrong
and so, after much deliberation, we are going to kill you'), mistakes will
be made and innocent people put to death. That alone is reason to abjure
capital punishment, as the notorious A6 murder case demonstrates.
True Stories begins a new series (10.00 C4) by reconsidering the execution
of James Hanratty for the murder of Michael Gregsten in 1962. Nobody who has
read Paul Foot's excellent book 'Who Killed Hanratty?' will need convincing,
but it is as well to keep reminding ourselves that we, society, hanged the
wrong man.
Another series which has done outstanding work in revealing miscarriages of
justice, and not only in the courts, is Taking Liberties, which returns to
BBC2 (8.00). Today David Jessel reports on the dangers of general
anaesthetics at the dentist's. There have been warnings, it seems, for 25
years, yet people, mostly young, go on dying. Also back with a fresh batch
is Harry Enfield's Television Programme (9.00 BBC2), the series in which the
'Loadsamoney' comedian has established a whole raft of new comedy
characters.
