<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Shake-up at Royal Mail is completed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL MAIL, the letters arm of the Post Office, yesterday put in place the
final pieces of a reorganisation which has cut management and administrative
staff by 3,500 and forced a further 9,000 managers to reapply for their
jobs.
The number of reporting levels between the managing director and the postal
worker delivering letters has been cut from nine to six. Headquarters staff
have been reduced from about 2,000 to 160.
The shake-up will result in annual savings of Pounds 60m to Pounds 70m.
Royal Mail says the savings are a 'secondary spin-off', however, and the
main purpose of the restructuring is to 'sharpen focus on the customer' by
devolving functions and responsibilities to a local level.
The UK's 64 former district head postmasters, for example, were replaced
yesterday by 88 area managers who are responsible for local customer
relations. Nine divisions, each with average turnover of Pounds 300m, have
replaced four territories and 64 districts. Each division is responsible -
'without excessive control from headquarters' - for sales, profit-and-loss
and local customer relations.
The shedding of management jobs has been completed without compulsory
redundancies. The top 1,000 managers have been through an assessment
programme run by Coopers and Lybrand Deloitte, the accountancy and
management consultancy firm. The rest have been assessed at the Post
Office's own management college at Rugby. Some have been demoted without
loss of pay while others have needed training.
Districts under the old structure had operating budgets, but were not
expected to generate revenue. Divisional directors and general managers are
now 'empowered to create profit', says Royal Mail. That could be done by
tailoring new services for local markets and by selling expertise and
innovations to the Post Office's other divisions.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
