<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 92 / Labour silent on cash aid to Jubilee Line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LABOUR party yesterday expressed support for extending London
Underground's Jubilee Line to Docklands. But it stopped short of offering to
provide funds if Olympia &amp; York, the property developer, failed to provide
its share of the finance.
O&amp;Y agreed under a proposal announced by the Department of Transport in 1989
to contribute Pounds 400m to the cost of the Pounds 1.3bn project, with the
rest coming from the government. There is also thought to be a smaller
contribution due from British Gas.
Ms Joan Ruddock, a shadow transport minister, said: 'We are not seeking any
variation of the proposals. The plan (for the extension) is there ready to
start. We want O&amp;Y to come up with the money.'
O&amp;Y, which is holding debt-restructuring talks with its banks, failed on
Tuesday to make its first scheduled contribution of Pounds 40m to the
project.
Ms Ruddock would not be drawn on any detailed response to reports that O&amp;Y
and its banks might seek to reduce their contribution to the project - a
move that would almost certainly shift the onus to the Treasury. 'We still
expect Olympia &amp; York or its bankers and British Gas to honour their
financial commitments to this scheme,' Ms Ruddock said. 'Clearly we want to
see whatever is on offer and see how best the contract can be drawn up.'
She added that, if O&amp;Y came up with its share, there was 'no reason why the
extension should no go ahead within the original timetable'.
Last week Mr John Prescott, Labour's senior transport spokesman, said the
project would be thrown into the hands of the public sector because the
private sector had failed to live up to its agreement.
The cautious line adopted by Labour yesterday is based partly on the hope
that O&amp;Y and its bankers will eventually rally round the project because
failure to do so might jeopardise the future of the company's Canary Wharf
development.
Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary and Labour's campaign
co-ordinator for London, said yesterday:
'The growing doubts over the Jubilee Line are only one symptom of the wider
failure of Conservative policy in the nation's capital.'
Letters, Page 19
