FT  02 APR 92 / UN force deployed in Cambodia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PHNOM PENH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations yesterday strengthened efforts to bring order to
Cambodia, sending Indonesian soldiers to monitor a ceasefire in the centre
of the country and announcing plans to deploy a further 4,000 peacekeeping
troops and police in the next few weeks.
The announcements by Mr Yasushi Akashi, head of the UN Transitional
Authority in Cambodia, and Lt Gen John Sanderson, the commander of UN
forces, were welcomed by diplomats and aid workers.
Fighting since January around Kompong Thom in central Cambodia between
leftist Khmer Rouge guerrillas and the Vietnamese-installed Cambodian
government had raised fears for the future of the peace accord signed in
Paris last year, and for the programme to repatriate 375,000 refugees from
Thailand.
A meeting yesterday of the Supreme National Council, a body which brings
together leaders of the main Cambodian factions agreed that returning
refugees would not be prosecuted.
Officials of the UN High Commission for Refugees, meanwhile, said they would
be allowed to visit Khmer Rouge-controlled territory in Battambang province
for the first time next week to look for suitable land for returnees.
